# Team Phoenix EEG Final Project (Beginner-Friendly Guide)

This repository is a **shared project version** prepared for review (for example, by instructors).
It contains the pipeline code, milestone outputs, reports, and helper scripts in a clean structure.

---

## 1) What this repository is

This project studies EEG “prediction error” signals in a VR task and shows a full processing workflow:

- load recordings,
- clean/filter EEG,
- create events/epochs,
- compute evoked responses and metrics,
- generate final reports.

It is organized as a milestone-style academic project, so each stage is easy to inspect.

---

## 2) Important: this is a filtered/shareable version

To keep this GitHub repo easy to share and review, large/raw dataset folders were removed.

### Included
- Pipeline code and step-by-step modules
- Milestone outputs and reports
- Runner scripts and documentation

### Not included
- Full raw subject dataset folders used for complete reprocessing from scratch
- Local virtual environments and bulky legacy data folders

So, this repository is ideal for **understanding the project and reviewing outputs**.
If you want to rerun everything from raw data, you must add the raw BIDS data separately.

---

## 3) Quick tour of the root folders

- `milestone2/`
	- Early milestone visual outputs (continuous EEG and ERP examples).

- `milestone3/`
	- Milestone 3 deliverables and showcase outputs.

- `milestone4/`
	- Milestone 4 scripts and documentation for pipeline progression.

- `milestone5/`
	- Final outputs and reports (including grand-average results and summary artifacts).

- `pipeline_steps/`
	- Beginner-friendly breakdown of the EEG pipeline into ordered steps:
		- load
		- filter/resample
		- bad channel handling
		- ICA artifact handling
		- events/trials
		- epoch/reject
		- evoked/metrics

- `scripts/`
	- Core runnable scripts used in the project workflow.

- `Run_the_Project/`
	- PowerShell helper scripts and run instructions for common project tasks.

- `PIPELINE_FLOW.md`
	- High-level map of how the full workflow moves from raw input to final report.

- `milestones_index.md`
	- Single-page milestone navigation.

---

## 4) Where to start (first-time reader)

If this is your first time reading the project, follow this order:

1. `milestones_index.md` (big picture)
2. `PIPELINE_FLOW.md` (how pipeline steps connect)
3. `pipeline_steps/README.md` and `pipeline_steps/config.py` (technical core)
4. `milestone5/README.md` and `milestone5/reports/` (final outcomes)

This order helps you understand **what was done**, then **how it was done**.

---

## 5) How to run things (simple)

Use the helper folder:

- `Run_the_Project/README.md`
- `Run_the_Project/run_all_subjects.ps1`
- `Run_the_Project/rerun_final_aggregation.ps1`
- `Run_the_Project/open_main_report.ps1`

These are convenience scripts for common actions.

### Note on re-running from scratch
Because this shared repo excludes raw data, full end-to-end reprocessing requires adding the raw BIDS dataset first.

---

## 6) Main outputs you can inspect immediately

- Milestone 2 visual examples in `milestone2/continuous_data_of_one_subject/`
- Milestone 3 showcase outputs in `milestone3/sub-1-outputs/`
- Final milestone reports and summaries in `milestone5/reports/`
- Final grand-average outputs in `milestone5/final_pipeline/`

---

## 7) Study context (short version)

The underlying study used a VR reach-to-object task and measured EEG responses to expected vs mismatched feedback.
In simple terms: the analysis looks for brain-signal differences when feedback is normal versus unexpectedly altered.

Reference publication:
- Gehrke et al., CHI 2019, “Detecting Visuo-Haptic Mismatches in Virtual Reality using Prediction Error Negativity of Event-Related Brain Potentials”
- DOI: https://doi.org/10.1145/3290605.3300657

---

## 8) In one sentence

This is a clean, beginner-friendly, shareable EEG pipeline project repository with milestone outputs and documentation, prepared for easy review and demonstration.